= The Resignation of Mikhail Gorbachev

President Mikhail Gorbachev has resigned. The red flag has been lowered from the Kremlin, and with it, seventy years of Soviet history come to an end.

What began as a bid to revitalize the Union—through Perestroika, Glasnost, and a “new thinking” in foreign policy—unraveled under the weight of contradictions. Economic stagnation, ethnic unrest, and growing demands for sovereignty shattered the unity of the state. The failed August coup, meant to save the USSR, only hastened its end.

Gorbachev departs not as a conqueror nor as a martyr, but as a man overtaken by the currents he tried to master. In the streets of Moscow, people cheer—and others mourn.

The Union is no more. What comes next is unknown.

