With Gorbachev’s resignation now public and irreversible, attention turns to the legal dissolution of the Soviet state.

Though much of the Union had already functionally ceased to exist, with republics declaring independence, ministries standing idle, and power shifting to Moscow, the legal architecture of the USSR still lingers. The Council of Republics of the Supreme Soviet, a little-known upper chamber created in 1990, now takes center stage.
  
